To build a production-ready AI resume and job matching platform as an AI student using Python, you should move away from simple prototyping tools (like Streamlit) and adopt a "Decoupled Architecture". This setup ensures your app is fast, secure, and can handle many users simultaneously. 
1. Production-Ready Tech Stack (2026 Standard)
Layer 	Recommended Technology	Why for Production?
Frontend	Next.js (React) + Tailwind CSS	Best for SEO, page speed, and professional UI.
Backend	FastAPI (Python)	High-performance, asynchronous, and native support for AI models.
AI Engine	LangChain + spaCy	Industry standard for building LLM workflows and NER extraction.
Database	PostgreSQL + Pinecone	Postgres for user data; Pinecone for "Vector Search" to match resumes to jobs.
Deployment	Docker + Vercel / AWS	Containers ensure the app runs the same everywhere.
2. Core Features Implementation
A. The "ATS-Proof" Resume Parser 
Don't just extract text; use Named Entity Recognition (NER) to identify specific skills and experience levels. 
Extraction: Use pdfminer.six or PyMuPDF for high-accuracy PDF parsing.
Scoring: Implement a weighted scoring algorithm (e.g., 50% technical skills, 25% experience, 25% education) rather than just keyword counting.
Semantic Matching: Use Sentence-Transformers to calculate the Cosine Similarity between a resume and a job description. This finds matches based on meaning, not just exact words. 
B. Job Aggregation Engine
To get "all jobs on the internet" in one place, use a mix of APIs and web scraping:
Aggregator APIs: Connect to Adzuna or Jooble to pull thousands of live listings instantly.
Scraping (Advanced): Use BeautifulSoup or Playwright to crawl specific niche job boards your competitors might miss. 
3. Production Essentials (Don't Skip These!)
Security: Never store raw resumes in your database. Use AWS S3 for file storage and encrypt sensitive user data.
CORS Configuration: Since your Next.js frontend and FastAPI backend are separate, you must configure FastAPI Middleware to allow them to communicate.
CI/CD Pipeline: Use GitHub Actions to automatically test and deploy your code whenever you push an update.
Environment Variables: Store your API keys (OpenAI, Database, etc.) in .env files and never commit them to GitHub. 
4. Recommended Project Roadmap
Backend MVP: Create a FastAPI endpoint /parse-resume that takes a PDF and returns JSON data using pyresparser.
Matching Logic: Integrate an LLM (like GPT-4o-mini) to provide "Resume Strength" feedback.
Frontend: Build a clean dashboard in Next.js where users can see their score and a list of "Highly Suitable" job links.
Containerize: Write a Dockerfile to package your Python backend for easy deployment. 
